pmc Sci Rep Sci Rep 1579 scirep Scientific Reports 2045-2322 Nature Publishing Group PMC12489039 PMC12489039.1 12489039 12489039 41034248 10.1038/s41598-025-15541-4 15541 1 Article Rapid thrombogenesis prediction in COVID-19 patients using DNN with data labeling Lee Joong-Lyul joonglyul.lee@gnu.ac.kr 1 Zhao Haitao 2 Tree Mike 3 Cristobal Angelo 4 1 https://ror.org/00saywf64 grid.256681.e 0000 0001 0661 1492 Department of Software Engineering, Gyeongsang National University, 2 https://ror.org/05pckj715 grid.266861.d 0000 0000 8749 8411 Department of Mathematics and Computer Science, University of North Carolina at Pembroke, 3 https://ror.org/01a21pk29 grid.455446.2 0000 0004 8351 3679 Corvid Technologies, 4 1 10 2025 2025 15 478255 34195 11 1 2025 8 8 2025 01 10 2025 03 10 2025 03 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ The rapid spread of COVID-19 globally has led to a surge in patients, among whom the incidence of blood clotting has been observed. This phenomenon poses a significant risk, potentially leading to cerebral hemorrhage and severe complications. Early detection of such blood clotting events is crucial for timely intervention and management of secondary complications. Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) simulations offer a means to detect these clotting phenomena, albeit with a drawback of time-intensive confirmation, spanning from several days to months. To address this challenge, we propose a framework for early detection of blood clotting events utilizing a deep neural network model. Leveraging patient-specific data derived from CFD simulations, our model learns to predict clotting events, expediting the diagnostic process. Hyperparameter tuning was employed to optimize the deep neural network algorithm for enhanced accuracy and performance. Furthermore, our framework facilitated comparative simulations across various machine learning algorithms, aiding in the identification of optimal data sizes for achieving high predictive accuracy. By combining computational modeling with machine learning techniques, our approach offers a promising avenue for expedited detection and management of thrombogenesis phenomena in COVID-19 patients. Keywords COVID-19 Deep neural network Health care Machine learning Subject terms Computational biology and bioinformatics Health care North Carolina Collaboratory SLFRP0129 SLFRP0129 SLFRP0129 SLFRP0129 pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement no pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © Springer Nature Limited 2025 Introduction In the medical field, technological advancements have catalyzed significant changes, particularly through the application of artificial intelligence to novel areas or historically challenging problems. Notably, Deep Neural Networks (DNN) have garnered considerable attention within artificial intelligence circles due to their exceptional performance and have found widespread utility in medical applications 1 4 The emergence of a global pandemic in recent years led to a surge in patients presenting with various symptoms, prompting extensive research that revealed a high incidence of blood clotting phenomena among afflicted individuals 5 10 11 Machine Learning (ML) stands poised to mitigate the time and expertise required for patient-specific cardiovascular flow modeling, potentially transforming it into a bedside clinical tool. The ability for non-experts in fluid mechanics to swiftly acquire additional information from patient-specific cardiovascular flow modeling can empower clinicians to predict disease progression, bridge gaps in medical imaging, and facilitate personalized clinical decision-making processes 12 This study delves into the intricacies of carotid artery anatomy to derive patient-specific risk assessments for potentially hazardous blood clot formation. Risk assessment hinges on predicting carotid artery wall shear stress levels, a parameter strongly correlated with blood clot-induced strokes 13 14 Our contribution lies in the proposal of a framework leveraging DNN for the early detection of thrombogenesis, addressing the time-consuming nature of this endeavor as illustrated in Fig. 1 Figure 1 Overview of rapid thrombogenesis prediction framework in Covid-19 patients using DNN. Contribution of this paper The paper makes several notable contributions, outlined below. We introduce a framework for early thrombogenesis risk detection using DNN, drastically reducing the time required compared to conventional CFD simulations—from several weeks to mere minutes. We explore various ML algorithms to predict rapid thrombogenesis risk metrics in the carotid artery, determining optimal training data sizes to minimize future data synthesis requirements from costly CFD simulations. Additionally, we employ rigorous hyperparameter tuning via RayTune to identify optimal variable configurations, enhancing the efficacy of the proposed framework and achieving a highly reliable model that maintains high accuracy using source labels and parallel coordination tools, even as the datasets increase. Related work Results Discussion Dataset and methods Conclusions Related work Machine learning (ML) algorithms have become indispensable tools in the medical field for managing and diagnosing diseases, thereby enhancing patient treatment and disease management. Across various medical domains, ML techniques have been extensively explored. In psychiatry, increasing success has been observed with machine and deep learning methods, particularly in data-rich environments 2 4 Identification of vulnerable plaque progression in mice, a condition associated with strokes, has been achieved using Support Vector Machine (SVM) and Decision Tree (DT) methods 15 16 Mechanical retrieval of thrombotic material from acute ischemic stroke has been investigated, emphasizing the urgency in stroke management 17 18 The importance of carotid artery stenting (CAS) in preventing strokes, particularly in predicting readmissions following CAS procedures, has been highlighted 19 20 21 Neural networks have been utilized to predict pressure drop and wall shear stress values in cardiovascular simulations, demonstrating the applicability of ML in cardiovascular research 1 22 In the domain of pulmonary embolism diagnosis, a knowledge-based hybrid learning algorithm (KBANN) has been proposed, enhancing diagnostic accuracy using modified criteria. The proposed KBANN outperforms purely empirical machine learning algorithms, showcasing its effectiveness in leveraging specialized domain knowledge for enhanced classification performance 23 24 Multimodal fusion models integrating clinical and imaging data have been proposed for improved disease detection 25 26 ANN models have been employed for predicting clinical outcomes in patients with acute lower-gastrointestinal hemorrhage, demonstrating superior predictive accuracy compared to traditional methods 27 28 Preprocessing techniques have been explored for improving the accuracy of lung cancer detection, showcasing advancements in image processing and classification 29 30 Furthermore, optimized neural computing techniques have been proposed for enhancing the accuracy of lung cancer detection 31 32 In our previous study, we proposed a framework utilizing machine learning for early detection of blood clot 33 Results DNN simulation results  Table 1 SVR results by cross-validation (CV). k Avg MSE Avg MAE Avg \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
