were related to specified flow through the geometry for each CFD simulation. The CFD simulation required specifying flow rate through the geometry as a function of time, static pressure at the geometry inlets and outlets as a function of time, and fluid viscosity. The flow rate was defined via a transient curve deconstructed using a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) algorithm to include its most influential frequencies. The 10 most prevalent FFT frequencies were saved as a vector and grouped as a single parameter. The mean flow rate and cardiac cycle period for each simulation was also recorded as a varied parameter. The geometry inlet and outlet transient pressures as a function of time were constructed using a 3-element Windkessel model to represent the influence of the rest of the circulatory system. Each Windkessel model included parameters for proximal and distal blood vessel resistance as well as vessel wall compliance and an initial pressure. The values for each of these variables within the Windkessel model representing the influence of the internal and external carotid arteries on the CFD simulation were also recorded. The specification of fluid viscosity from the CFD simulation involved a non-linear viscosity model from which the maximum possible viscosity value was recorded. Finally, the CFD simulation input cross-sectional area and normal vector were recorded for each of the 5 geometries. Table 6 10 11 12 The CFD simulations conducted consumed between 5,000 and 38,500 cpu-hours of resources and were post-processed to produce two key metrics related to blood clots: mean time-averaged wall shear stress (mean_tawss) and fluid washout. The mean_tawss is a measure of the friction force existing between the fluid and the artery wall. The mean_tawss was computed by averaging the wall shear stress value at each point of the discretized fluid domain adjacent to the artery wall. The averaging procedure was conducted both temporally over the cardiac cycle and spatially over the entire artery wall. This resulted in a single value for each CFD simulation. The fluid washout metric was represented as a percentage of neutrally-buoyant Lagrangian particles present in the fluid domain after a set amount of time. The CFD simulation was seeded with 1000 particles at the beginning of the last cardiac cycle and the percentage was computed using the ratio of particles that left the domain during the final simulated cardiac cycle. Table 7 Data preprocessing and normalization Figure 13 13 14 15 14 15 14 15 16 16 16 6 1 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
