				\begin{document}$$\delta _i$$\end{document} Conclusions The phenomenon of blood clotting, a common complication among COVID-19 patients, can be prevented from progressing into a serious condition if detected early. Currently, detecting blood clots through CFD analysis can take several days to weeks, which presents significant challenges. To address this issue, we have proposed a framework that utilizes a DNN model alongside 10 different machine learning models, effectively reducing the time required for analysis. In our simulation using SVR with CV, we achieved an accuracy of over 92% with 9-fold CV. Building on these findings, we evaluated 11 different models, with XGBoost, Logistic Regression, and Decision Tree models demonstrating accuracies exceeding 95%. Furthermore, we conducted a simulation to determine the optimal data size, with XGBoost showing exceptional performance with datasets containing at least 30 samples. However, as the data size increased, the model’s accuracy significantly deteriorated. To improve the model’s reliability, we added a new data label column, which enhanced its robustness. Additionally, our approach incorporates patient-specific vascular geometries derived from medical imaging to perform CFD simulations. Hemodynamic parameters—such as wall shear stress and residence time—are extracted and used to train ML models for thrombosis risk prediction. We believe our proposed framework holds great potential for accurately and rapidly diagnosing blood clots in COVID-19 patients, thereby improving patient care. Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements This project is supported by the North Carolina Collaboratory at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill with funding appropriated by the North Carolina General Assembly via the American Rescue Plan Act of 2021 (H.R. 1319) (federal award identification number SLFRP0129). Auth